## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code contains three Thread.Abort patterns:

| API | Pattern | Line |
|-----|---------|------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | Called when `Join(timeout)` fails |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow | Catches the injected abort |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue execution | Swallows the abort |

All three throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`).

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|--------------------------|----------------|-----|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(() => work(), token)` | Task-based model; token prevents scheduling if already cancelled |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(cts.Token)` | `WaitAsync` unblocks the caller when the token fires (.NET 6+) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Cooperative cancellation — the timeout auto-cancels the source |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | `OperationCanceledException` is the cooperative equivalent |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No forced abort to reset — cancellation is voluntary |
| `catch (Exception ex) { error = ex; }` | *(removed)* | `Task.Run` captures exceptions automatically via the `Task` |
| Manual `AggregateException` throw | *(removed)* | `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` unwraps and rethrows the original exception |

---

### ⚠️ Critical Pitfall: Uncooperative Work

The biggest behavior difference:

```
.NET Framework:  Thread.Abort() forcibly kills the thread mid-execution
.NET 8:          CancellationToken only works if `work()` checks it
```

If `work()` is a tight CPU loop or a blocking synchronous call that **never checks the token**, the work **continues running in the background** even after `TimeoutException` is thrown. The caller unblocks, but the thread pool thread keeps working.

**If `work()` can cooperate**, accept a token:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
        return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller inserts checkpoints:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**If `work()` cannot cooperate** (third-party library, native call), move it to a child process and use `Process.Kill()` — that's the only true equivalent to `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET.

---

### Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Forgetting `using` on CancellationTokenSource** | Leaks an internal timer. Always dispose it. |
| **`Task.Run` + `.Result` without `WaitAsync`** | `.Result` blocks forever if work hangs — `WaitAsync(token)` lets you bail out. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from a caller's cancellation. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only fires at the next `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or async await point. Large gaps between checks = delayed cancellation. |
